_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":null,"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":69000,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"post_url":"/t/running-candle-off-of-rio-pwm/495084/2","reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":null},{"id":3554919,"name":null,"username":"veg","avatar_template":"/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/v/3be4f8/{size}.png","created_at":"2025-03-12T11:27:24.648Z","cooked":"<p>I have never used a CANdle, but I think I see the problem. You are trying to use the AddressableLED class to control the CANdle, but these are two different methods for controlling an LED string.</p>
<p>AddressableLED is meant to be used without a CANdle. You would connect the GND and DATA IN lines of your LED strip directly to a Rio <span class="abbreviation">PWM<template class="tooltiptext" data-text="Pulse Width Modulation"></template></span> port, and then use the AddressableLED class to generate patterns and animations. This method allows your robot code to directly set LED colors and patterns, but requires a bit more code.</p>
<p>The CANdle is meant to simplify the coding for you by handling all the animations itself. You configure the CANdle to know about a set of animations you want it to do, and then you use a <span class="abbreviation">PWM<template class="tooltiptext" data-text="Pulse Width Modulation"></template></span> signal from the Rio to tell the CANdle which pattern to show at any moment. In this situation, your robot code is never directly setting LED R,G,B values.</p>
<p>I suspect what is happening is that the Rio is sending out the AddressableLED control signal, which you have wired into your CANdle to be interpreted as a simple <span class="abbreviation">PWM<template class="tooltiptext" data-text="Pulse Width Modulation"></template></span> duty cycle signal. The CANdle is randomly switching between your different preset animations based on this incorrectly interpreted signal.</p>
<p>You can either change your code to send a regular <span class="abbreviation">PWM<template class="tooltiptext" data-text="Pulse Width Modulation"></template></span> signal out to the CANdle, or you can eliminate the CANdle, wire your LED strip directly to the Rio, and use the AddressableLED class to command your animations from robot code.</p>","post_number":3,"post_type":1,"posts_count":5,"updated_at":"2025-03-12T11:28:46.589Z","reply_count":1,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":0,"reads":48,"readers_count":47,"score":14.6,"yours":false,"topic_id":495084,"topic_slug":"running-candle-off-of-rio-pwm","display_username":null,"primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":null,"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":48088,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":""},"post_url":"/t/running-candle-off-of-rio-pwm/495084/3","reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":null},{"id":3554956,"name":"Joe Ross","username":"Joe_Ross","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/joe_ross/{size}/37_2.png","created_at":"2025-03-12T12:46:43.463Z","cooked":"<aside class="quote no-group" data-username="veg" data-post="3" data-topic="495084">
<div class="title">
<div class="quote-controls"></div>
<img loading="lazy" alt="" width="24" height="24" src="https://www.chiefdelphi.com/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/v/3be4f8/48.png" class="avatar"> veg:</div>
<blockquote>
<p>I have never used a CANdle, but I think I see the problem. You are trying to use the AddressableLED class to control the CANdle, but these are two different methods for controlling an LED string.</p>
</blockquote>
</aside>
<p>From the CANdle site:</p>
<blockquote>
<ul>
<li>Firmware supports <strong>direct LED value control</strong> via <strong><span class="abbreviation">CAN<template class="tooltiptext" data-text="Controller Area Network"></template></span> bus/<span class="abbreviation">CAN<template class="tooltiptext" data-text="Controller Area Network"></template></span> FD</strong> <strong>(Phoenix)</strong> or <strong>WS2812B-compliant pulse-train</strong>.</li>
<li><strong>Auto-detection</strong> of <strong><span class="abbreviation">CAN<template class="tooltiptext" data-text="Controller Area Network"></template></span> bus/<span class="abbreviation">CAN<template class="tooltiptext" data-text="Controller Area Network"></template></span> FD</strong> <strong>(Phoenix)</strong> or <strong>WS2812B-compliant pulse-train</strong>. No software configuration required to choose between the two.</li>
</ul>
</blockquote>
<p>They’re trying to do the latter.</p>","post_number":4,"post_type":1,"posts_count":5,"updated_at":"2025-03-12T12:46:43.463Z","reply_count":1,"reply_to_post_number":3,"quote_count":1,"incoming_link_count":0,"reads":35,"readers_count":34,"score":27.0,"yours":false,"topic_id":495084,"topic_slug":"running-candle-off-of-rio-pwm","display_username":"Joe Ross","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":"","bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[{"id":2,"count":1}],"moderator":true,"admin":false,"staff":true,"user_id":65,"hidden":false,"trust_level":4,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"post_url":"/t/running-candle-off-of-rio-pwm/495084/4","reactions":[{"id":"+1","type":"emoji","count":1}],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":1,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":null},{"id":3554967,"name":null,"username":"veg","avatar_template":"/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/v/3be4f8/{size}.png","created_at":"2025-03-12T13:11:06.752Z","cooked":"<p>So the CANdle is doing voltage regulation, and passing the WS2812B pulse through?</p>
<p>I would probably try to isolate the problem by connecting the Rio <span class="abbreviation">PWM<template class="tooltiptext" data-text="Pulse Width Modulation"></template></span> pin directly to the DI of the LED strip while still using the CANdle for voltage regulation.</p>","post_number":5,"post_type":1,"posts_count":5,"updated_at":"2025-03-12T13:11:06.752Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_number":4,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":0,"reads":25,"readers_count":24,"score":5.0,"yours":false,"topic_id":495084,"topic_slug":"running-candle-off-of-rio-pwm","display_username":null,"primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":null,"reply_to_user":{"id":65,"username":"Joe_Ross","name":"Joe Ross","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/joe_ross/{size}/37_2.png"},"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":48088,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":""},"post_url":"/t/running-candle-off-of-rio-pwm/495084/5","reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":null}],"stream":[3553550,3553873,3554919,3554956,3554967]},"timeline_lookup":[[1,146],[2,145],[3,144]],"suggested_topics":[{"id":493797,"title":"PID","fancy_title":"PID","slug":"pid","posts_count":4,"reply_count":1,"highest_post_number":4,"image_url":null,"created_at":"2025-03-02T00:35:07.290Z","last_posted_at":"2025-03-02T01:11:08.485Z","bumped":true,"bumped_at":"2025-03-02T01:11:08.485Z","archetype":"regular","unseen":false,"pinned":